data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction won't compile. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// EF Core 10
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All that expression-tree plumbing is gone — conditionals work directly inside the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes that generate rename migrations

**Duplicate property names across complex types** are now uniquified (e.g., `Street` → `Street1`). **Nested complex types** now include the full path (`Complex_NestedComplex_Property` instead of `NestedComplex_Property`).

Your `ShippingAddress.Street` / `BillingAddress.Street` and `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` are both affected. Fix by pinning column names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(x => x.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(x => x.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types — pin to the old shorter name
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, a =>
        {
            // Was "BillingAddress_City", now would be "Payment_BillingAddress_City"
            a.Property(x => x.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Otherwise, `dotnet ef migrations add` will generate column renames that could break existing data.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your class won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter (redacted SQL for logging)
    {
        // Use logCommandText for safe logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add the same `string logCommandText` parameter to **all** other methods you implement (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
